<section xml:id="s_isom_thms_C" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Fourth isomorphism theorem</title>

    <theorem xml:id="th_isom_thms_4">
    <title>Fourth isomorphism theorem</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>\phi\colon G\rightarrow H</m> be a surjective homomorphism, and let <m>N=\ker\phi</m>. Define 
    <md>
        <mrow>\mathcal{S}_{G,N} \amp =\{K\subseteq G \colon N\leq K\leq G\}</mrow>
        <mrow>\mathcal{S}_H \amp =\{K\subseteq H\mid K\leq H\}</mrow>
    </md>.
    In other words, <m>\mathcal{S}_{G,N}</m> is the set of all subgroups of <m>G</m> containing <m>N</m>, and <m>\mathcal{S}_H</m> is the set of all subgroups of <m>H</m>.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                There is a bijective correspondence between <m>\mathcal{S}_{G,N}</m> and <m>\mathcal{S}_H</m> given as follows:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="im_4th_isom" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Fourth isomorphism theorem bijection</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                \mathcal{S}_{G,N} \arrow[r,leftrightarrow] \amp H \\
                K\arrow[r,mapsto] \amp \phi(K) \\
                \phi^{-1}(K) \amp K \arrow[l,mapsto]
                \end{tikzcd}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For <m>K,K'\in \mathcal{S}_{G,N}</m>, we have 
                <mdn>
                    <mrow>K \text{ normal } \amp \iff \phi(K) \text{ normal} </mrow>
                    <mrow>K\subseteq K' \amp \iff \phi(K)\subseteq \phi(K')</mrow>
                    <mrow>\phi(K\cap K') \amp = \phi(K)\cap \phi(K')</mrow>
                    <mrow>\phi(\angvec{K,K'}) \amp =\angvec{\phi(K),\phi(K')}</mrow>

                </mdn>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_4th_isom_thm">
        <title>Fourth isomorphism theorem: quotients</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>N</m> be a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>. The subgroups of <m>G/N</m> are in bijective correspondence with the subgroups of <m>G</m> containing <m>N</m>. Furthermore, this correspondence preserves normality, inclusion, intersection, generated subgroups, <etc/>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>

</section>